For huge companies, when a Confluence admin create a new user, they'd like that they can create a Personal Space for the new user with some default customised content in the personal space (eg. profile). The API is [available|http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/CONFDEV/Confluence+XML-RPC+and+SOAP+APIs#ConfluenceXML-RPCandSOAPAPIs-Spaces], but it'd be better if Confluence admin  can do this through the UI.

Exporting to PDF a page containing \{jira\} macros results in an unreadable rendering:

{panel:title=Screenshots of macro rendered in Chrome (HTML) and Acrobat (PDF)}!confluence-pdf-render-issue.png!{panel}

It seems that the PDF renderer misses out on the _padding-left_ and _background-repeat_ style attributes used by the macro.

The Confluence source text used was {noformat}* {jira:MOPS-531}
* {jira:MOPS-530}{noformat}

Using Chrome's inspect element, I can see that the first macro expanded to this HTML:{code:html}
<span class="jira-issue">
  <a style="background-image: url('http://jira/images/icons/bug.gif')"
     href="http://jira/browse/MOPS-531">MOPS-531</a>
   - Incorrect penetration rate data generated by JActionDrill - 
   <span class="jira-status">SCOPED</span>
</span>
{code}
And that the _jira-issue_ class is styled by {{confluence.extra.jira:common-resources.css}}:
{code}.jira-issue > a {
    background-repeat: no-repeat;
    padding-left: 20px;
    padding-bottom: 2px;
    font-weight: bold;
}{code}

We need to be able to export these pages to PDF for site engineers without comms access.

h3. Fix

Install version 1.14 or newer of the Confluence PDF Export plugin, which can be downloaded at the [Atlassian Plugin Exchange|https://plugins.atlassian.com/plugin/details/24681].

