For Confluence 3.4 and earlier, Crowd could be used to manage extremely large user bases using Crowd delegation to LDAP with local group management.  Now that Confluence is doing a full directory sync, large Crowd directories bring instances to a standstill with a similar performance hit that we see with large LDAP instances.  There is an incremental sync option, but that requires an initial sync to finish successfully, which could still be a barrier.

There are also instances where organizations need Confluence to call to Crowd for group memberships on each login to immediately pull new group memberships providing Can Use and prevent limbo (which can last as long as the sync interval), much like the delegated LDAP connector in Confluence.  Setting the sync interval to be very small will spam the logs and isn't an ideal solution.

The Crowd Connector should have a delegated option similar to the delegated LDAP connector such that syncs against very large Crowd user and group bases are possible.

